# Design & Code Quality

This app uses **Next.js 16, React 19, and Tailwind CSS v4**. Every UI must look like a polished, hand-crafted Figma design — never a generic AI-generated template.

## Design Language (look like it came from Figma)

Avoid the default "AI look": purple/indigo gradients, centered hero with a giant emoji, glassmorphism on everything, identical rounded cards everywhere, generic `shadow-lg` boxes.

Instead:

- **Deliberate spacing & hierarchy** — use a consistent spacing scale (`gap-2/4/6/8`), clear type scale, and intentional alignment. Whitespace is a design choice, not an accident.
- **Restrained, intentional color** — define colors as CSS variables / `@theme` tokens in `globals.css` and use them via Tailwind tokens. No random hex values scattered in markup.
- **Subtle depth** — prefer thin borders (`border border-black/5`) and soft, low-opacity shadows over heavy drop shadows and glows.
- **Consistent radii & components** — pick one radius scale and reuse shared components; don't reinvent a button/card per page.
- **Real content layout** — design for actual data and states (empty, loading, error), not lorem-ipsum placeholders.

## Typography (corporate)

- **Font: IBM Plex Sans only.** It is loaded via `next/font` in `layout.js` and exposed as the `--font-sans` token. Never import or reference any other font family (no Geist, Arial, system fallbacks in markup).
- Use the `font-sans` utility (default on `body`); never hardcode `font-family` in components.
- Available weights: **400 / 500 / 600 / 700**. Don't use weights outside this set.
- Use the `--text-*` scale with appropriate `--leading-*` line-heights. Keep type restrained and consistent — corporate, not flashy.

## Pixel-Perfect Implementation

- **Match the reference exactly** — when a Figma/screenshot reference is given, replicate spacing, font sizes, weights, colors, radii, and borders precisely. Eyeball nothing.
- **Use the design tokens** defined in `src/app/globals.css` (`@theme`). Map design values to the nearest token; if a needed value is missing, add a token there — never hardcode raw `px`/hex in components.
- **Stick to the 4px grid** — all spacing comes from the Tailwind scale (driven by `--spacing`). Avoid arbitrary one-off values like `mt-[13px]`.
- **Exact typography** — use the `--text-*` scale and correct `font-weight`/`line-height`; don't approximate sizes.
- **Account for every state** — hover, focus (visible ring), active, disabled, loading, and empty states, matching the design.
- **Verify** — compare against the reference at 100% zoom before considering it done.

## Styling Rules

- **No inline styles.** Never use the `style={{ ... }}` prop.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
<div style={{ padding: 16, background: "#fff", borderRadius: 8 }}>

// ✅ GOOD
<div className="p-4 bg-background rounded-lg">
```

- Style with **Tailwind utility classes**. For dynamic values, drive them through Tailwind tokens / CSS variables defined in `globals.css`, not inline `style`.
- The only acceptable use of `style` is binding a runtime-only CSS variable (e.g. `style={{ "--progress": value }}`) — and only when there is no Tailwind alternative.
- Reuse shared UI components instead of duplicating class strings across files.

## Clean Code

- **No dead or filler code** — no unused imports, variables, props, commented-out blocks, or placeholder `console.log`.
- **No narration comments.** Only comment non-obvious intent or constraints.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
// increment the counter
setCount(count + 1);

// ✅ GOOD (only when intent is non-obvious)
// debounce to avoid hammering the radar API on every keystroke
```

- Keep components small and single-purpose; extract reusable logic into hooks and shared components.
- Use clear, descriptive names; prefer early returns over deep nesting.
- Write only what the task needs — no speculative abstractions or "just in case" options.
